1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,359
Most AI decision tools give a team one confident answer.

2
00:00:03,359 --> 00:00:11,422
Dissent Garden keeps the disagreement you cannot afford to
lose, binds every claim to supplied evidence, and turns
uncertainty into the next reversible test.

3
00:00:11,422 --> 00:00:17,981
Here is a product choice: launch a new onboarding flow to
everyone, or stage it at ten percent.

4
00:00:17,981 --> 00:00:25,633
The evidence includes an activation lift, an unexplained
Android crash regression, no weekend support, successful
rollback drills, and a flexible campaign.

5
00:00:25,633 --> 00:00:28,184
Each fact has a stable evidence ID.

6
00:00:28,184 --> 00:00:36,414
Codex helped build and verify the complete product: contracts,
interface, failure boundaries, browser quality assurance, and
seventeen automated tests.

7
00:00:36,414 --> 00:00:37,714
At runtime, GPT-5.

8
00:00:37,714 --> 00:00:42,912
6 Sol runs Builder, Breaker, and Grounder in isolation and in
parallel.

9
00:00:42,912 --> 00:00:44,211
A fourth GPT-5.

10
00:00:44,211 --> 00:00:48,110
6 pass adjudicates only after all three are complete.

11
00:00:48,110 --> 00:00:50,096
The result is not a vote.

12
00:00:50,096 --> 00:00:54,401
Dissent Garden recommends a ten percent Monday stage, not a
full Friday release.

13
00:00:54,401 --> 00:01:00,362
It preserves the activation upside while refusing to ignore
the Android reliability regression and the weekend support
gap.

14
00:01:00,362 --> 00:01:02,586
Each seat has a different obligation.

15
00:01:02,586 --> 00:01:04,809
Builder finds the strongest bounded proposal.

16
00:01:04,809 --> 00:01:07,404
Breaker exposes failure modes and displaced cost.

17
00:01:07,404 --> 00:01:10,369
Grounder audits the reasoning against the supplied evidence.

18
00:01:10,369 --> 00:01:15,929
They cannot imitate agreement because they do not see one
another before completing their passes.

19
00:01:15,929 --> 00:01:19,848
The arbiter separates atomic claims into survived, disputed,
and unsupported.

20
00:01:19,848 --> 00:01:27,295
Structured output is not enough by itself, so the server
allowlists every evidence ID and demotes evidence-free
survivor claims.

21
00:01:27,295 --> 00:01:30,430
A persuasive model response cannot silently invent support.

22
00:01:30,430 --> 00:01:33,709
The unresolved tension stays visible instead of being averaged
away.

23
00:01:33,709 --> 00:01:43,217
Then the system names the cheapest reversible test: a staffed
ten percent rollout with an Android stop threshold, a rollback
owner, and a review after five hundred activated users.

24
00:01:43,217 --> 00:01:45,818
Every decision enters a hash-chained append-only ledger.

25
00:01:45,818 --> 00:01:46,933
The live GPT-5.

26
00:01:46,933 --> 00:01:52,135
6 sample used six thousand seven hundred sixty-six tokens and
cost about eleven cents.

27
00:01:52,135 --> 00:02:01,796
Repeating the exact untouched decision then reused its
verified receipt in eighty-four milliseconds, with zero model
calls and all six thousand seven hundred sixty-six tokens
avoided.

28
00:02:01,796 --> 00:02:04,397
Corrections invalidate stale reuse without rewriting history.

29
00:02:04,397 --> 00:02:08,079
Plant a Seed turns one decision into a bounded living watch.

30
00:02:08,079 --> 00:02:13,100
Local checks stay free while evidence is repetitive and
tighten their wake threshold after noise.

31
00:02:13,100 --> 00:02:14,773
Material contradictions wake the seed.

32
00:02:14,773 --> 00:02:22,137
Before model work begins, the system must reserve its worst-
case cost against both the seed's dollar ceiling and the
global token budget.

33
00:02:22,137 --> 00:02:28,162
In this thirty-day simulation, twenty-six checks slept, five
woke, none were false wakes, and no budget was breached.

34
00:02:28,162 --> 00:02:39,005
Dissent Garden is a decision workspace for teams shipping
under uncertainty: disagreement that remains useful, evidence
that stays inspectable, memory that gets tighter, and agents
that must earn the right to spend again.
